European Defense and European Solidarity
PRAHA: Perhaps it is due to the experience of a man who had to endure forty years of communist rule, and before that, the occupation by the Nazis.
Perhaps it is due to the experience of living in a country in the heart of Europe, a place that for centuries has been the crossroads of Europe's intellectual currents, geopolitical interests, and confrontations.
Perhaps these factors, combined, have led me to conclude that Europe represents a single political unity whose security is indivisible.
The notion that there could be two Europes forever  one democratic, stable, prosperous, and integrated, the other less democratic, less stable, less prosperous, and isolated  is a mistake.
It is like heating up one part of a room while keeping another part cold.
There is only one Europe, despite its diversity.
Every significant event echoes throughout Europe.
If Europe is to become united, if the European Union is to integrate the new post-communist democracies – which is in Europe's interest – a series of essential tasks must be addressed, both within the new democracies and in the European and Atlantic communities.
First, Europe must foster community in the post-communist countries by restoring civil society.
For a vibrant society cannot be rebuilt from above.
Europe thus needs to help its new democracies become an organic part of a common continental commitment to deepen and strengthen civil society.
The more diverse European civil society structures become and the more they are interconnected, the better equipped the new democracies will be for EU membership and the more stable they will become as states.
To achieve this, Europe must encourage the new democracies to transfer diverse solidarity tasks to self-governing institutions and nonprofit or public service organizations.
The deeper the level of redistribution, the more transparent and economical it will be; and the better it will meet those social needs that central authorities cannot recognize.
Social solidarity will become more authentic when it is closely linked to people or their associations.
An authentic solidarity among people, social groups, settlements, and regions is also the safest foundation for those forms of solidarity that only states can exercise.
A bitter chapter in modern European history was the appeasement policy with its abandonment of European solidarity, which led to Munich's capitulation.
This experience is still a vigorous call for vigilance.
Evil must be confronted as soon as it appears; it is not enough for governments to act alone.
For government policy arises from the feelings of civil society, from the people.
Concern for security is indeed a manifestation of social solidarity.
The EU is working intensively on a new concept of its security policy.
It should distinguish itself by the ability to make quick decisions and to implement joint decisions swiftly – reforms that have been shown to be necessary by the recent developments in Yugoslavia.
The NATO intervention last year has shown that respect for human life and human freedom, as well as the interests of pan-European security, requires interventions beyond the EU borders.
The stronger the mandate for such an action, the better.
Unfortunately, there may be situations where the UN mandate does not come through, even though an intervention would be in the interest of many people, indeed of all of Europe, and even of human civilization.
Until recently, Europe was poorly prepared for this alternative.
It is now better prepared, at least psychologically.
This psychological readiness should be used to promote Europe's material and technical preparedness.
It also requires further measures in the field of preventive security, and more is needed so that this security reflects the values of Europe's extended civil society.
Thousands of lives and enormous amounts of material could have been saved in Kosovo, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and other parts of former Yugoslavia if the international community had acted at the onset of the conflict.
Despite warnings of impending horror, action was taken timidly.
These failures were the result of various individual domestic political interests as well as a lack of willingness to take risks for a good cause.
Without American energy, the international community would indeed still be witnessing the horror in Kosovo.
Europe cannot be permanently dependent on the USA, especially regarding European issues.
It must be capable of negotiating its own solutions.
It is unthinkable that the EU can be regarded as a respected part of the world order if it fails to negotiate means and methods to protect human rights not only on its own territory but also in regions that may join it someday.
Such an EU expansion is only feasible if it proceeds hand in hand with a bold reform of EU institutions.
I hope confidently that the government conference on institutional reform will present practical proposals for the advancement of the Union.
But I consider this as the beginning of a process that will likely take decades and should be guided by a sustained effort to accelerate and increase the transparency of EU decision-making.
A related point to the institutional reform is how to give smaller states the assurance that they will not simply be overridden by the larger ones, while still taking due account of the size of individual states.
A possibility is the establishment of a second chamber of the European Parliament; the members of this second chamber will be elected not directly, but from the ranks of the parliaments of the member states.
The first chamber of the EU – i.e., the current Parliament – would therefore reflect the size of the individual member states, while the second chamber, with the same number of representatives for each state, would enhance equality.
Eventually, these changes will require the EU to have a clear, understandable constitution – a text that all European children could learn.
Such a constitution requires two parts.
Part one would define the rights and duties of both European citizens and the states, the underlying values, and the significance and aims of integration.
Part two would describe the central institutions of the EU, their fundamental powers, and their relationships to each other.
Such a constitution would not mean an automatic transformation of the current Union into the federal overstate that eurosceptics fear.
It would, however, help the citizens of a integrating Europe to recognize what the EU stands for, better understand its significance for their lives, and consequently identify with it.
